In this modified example, the `SO_LINGER` option is set after accepting each new connection (on the client socket `client_fd`). This ensures that the `SO_LINGER` setting will be applied to the connection with the client, affecting the close behavior of that specific connection. This way, when you eventually close the client socket, it will immediately drop the connection without lingering, as specified by the `so_linger` struct settings (`l_onoff` set to 1 and `l_linger` set to 0).

Yes, you can set the `SO_LINGER` option on the listening socket; however, the effect it will have is not directly on the listening socket itself, but rather it may affect the client sockets that are accepted through this listening socket _if_ the socket options are inherited through `accept`.

However, keep in mind that on many systems, the `SO_LINGER` setting is not inherited by accepted sockets, and setting `SO_LINGER` on a listening socket does not typically serve a practical purpose. The `SO_LINGER` option is intended to control the behavior of an active connection during its closure phase. Since the listening socket itself does not send or receive data beyond accepting new connections, the linger behavior does not have a meaningful impact on it. It is the individual accepted connections (client sockets) that participate in sending and receiving data, and they are the sockets where you would need to specifically set `SO_LINGER`.

It is always good practice to set socket options explicitly for each accepted socket if you want to ensure specific behavior. This way, you are not reliant on the inheritance of socket options, which may vary across different operating systems and implementations. As shown in the previously corrected example, you would typically set the `SO_LINGER` option on the client socket after the `accept` call.

If you are experimenting or have a specific use case in mind where you believe setting `SO_LINGER` on the listening socket could have an impact, you can certainly do so in the same manner you would for any other socket using `setsockopt` before you call `listen`:

```c
struct linger so_linger;
so_linger.l_onoff = 1;  // Enable SO_LINGER
so_linger.l_linger = 0; // Set timeout of 0 seconds

// Set the SO_LINGER option on the listening socket
if (setsockopt(listen_fd, SOL_SOCKET, SO_LINGER, &so_linger, sizeof(so_linger)) < 0) {
    perror("setsockopt");
    close(listen_fd);
    return 1;
}
```

But keep in mind that to control the closing behavior of the sockets where data is actually sent and received (which is typically what you want), you should set the `SO_LINGER` option on each accepted client socket, not the listening socket.
